Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` without opening a real port. Then wire that client into the MCP C# SDK's transport.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add reference ../YourMcpServer           # your server project
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol          # official C# MCP SDK
```

### Test class

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests : IAsyncLifetime
{
    private WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory = null!;
    private IMcpClient _mcpClient = null!;

    public async Task InitializeAsync()
    {
        _factory = new WebApplicationFactory<Program>();

        // Get an HttpClient wired to the in-memory test server
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Use the SDK's Streamable HTTP transport with that client
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                // any other options (e.g. custom headers)
            },
            httpClient   // ← inject the test HttpClient here
        );

        _mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsExpectedTools()
    {
        var tools = await _mcpClient.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my-tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsCorrectResult()
    {
        var result = await _mcpClient.CallToolAsync(
            "my-tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" });

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains("expected output", result.Content[0].Text);
    }

    public async Task DisposeAsync()
    {
        await _mcpClient.DisposeAsync();
        await _factory.DisposeAsync();
    }
}
```

### Why this works

| Piece | Role |
|---|---|
| `WebApplicationFactory<Program>` | Hosts your full ASP.NET pipeline in-memory (middleware, DI, routing — everything) |
| `CreateClient()` | Returns an `HttpClient` backed by an in-memory `HttpMessageHandler` — no TCP socket |
| `SseClientTransport(…, httpClient)` | The MCP SDK transport accepts an external `HttpClient`, so it uses the in-memory one |

### Tips

- **Expose `Program`**: add `public partial class Program { }` at the bottom of your server's `Program.cs` (or use `InternalsVisibleTo`).
- **Override services**: use `_factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` to swap in test doubles.
- **Endpoint path**: match whatever your server maps (e.g. `/mcp`, `/sse`). Check your `app.MapMcp()` call.
- If your server uses the older SSE+POST transport instead of Streamable HTTP, use `SseClientTransport`; for the newer streamable HTTP transport, use `StreamableHttpClientTransport` — both accept an `HttpClient` parameter.
